children.subject: Due to the class standing restrictions, you will want to contact your ESS advisor if you are a frosh/sophomore with junior/senior standing. The department of the R&C will hopefully then provide the student with a CEC to enroll in the class as long as there is still seat availability. You can also contact the department directly and explain your situation and see if they will issue you a CEC directly.  If you are a frosh or sophomore and are placed on the waitlist, then you are on the waitlist.
The courses that seem to allow me only let me be on the wait-list.

history.content: Please contact your ESS Advisor (Bryan, Sharon, or Olivia).  Your ESS Advisor can contact the department of the R&C "B" course you want to take.  If you choose to email your advisor, include the course name and number as well as the CCN.  You may want to give them at least 3 different courses you are interested in taking in case the departments are unable to provide Course Entry Codes (CECs) for your first choice.  I suggest you contact the ESS Advisor as soon as possible before sophomore and frosh enrollment start and classes begin filling up.

children.subject: As far as I can tell, there's no surefire way, at least with the current system, to tell whether a given student is a freshman or sophomore (or junior or senior). Even the non-AP class standing can include transfer credits from college courses taken during high school, and counting the number of semesters that a student has been here is also iffy (withdrawals, failed semesters, and the like). At least humans can determine what's appropriate for a student's situation much better than Telebears can.
Yeah :) The worst part is that even your advisors are helpless!
This is just wrong! Why doesn't anyone fix this bug!
